com.github.dm.jrt.stream

Interface StreamChannel<IN,OUT>

  • Type Parameters:
    OUT - the output data type.
    All Superinterfaces:
    Channel<IN,OUT>, InvocationConfigurable<StreamChannel<IN,OUT>>, Iterable<OUT>, Iterator<OUT>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractStreamChannel

    public interface StreamChannel<IN,OUT>
extends Channel<IN,OUT>, InvocationConfigurable<StreamChannel<IN,OUT>>
    Interface defining a stream channel, that is, a channel concatenating map and reduce functions.
    Each function in the stream is backed by a routine instance, which may have its own specific configuration and invocation mode.

    To better document the effect of each method on the underlying stream, a StreamFlow annotation indicates for each one the type of transformation applied.

    Note that each START method may throw a StreamException if an unexpected error occurs while initiating the flow of data.
    Note also that, if at least one reduce function is part of the chain, the results will be propagated only when the previous routine invocations complete.

    Created by davide-maestroni on 12/23/2015.

      • appendGet

        @NotNull
 @StreamFlow(value=MAP)
StreamChannel<IN,OUT> appendGet(long count,
                                                                 @NotNull
                                                                 Supplier<? extends OUT> supplier)
        Concatenates a stream appending the outputs returned by the specified supplier.
        The supplier will be called count number of times only when the previous routine invocations complete. The count number must be positive.

        Note that the created routine will be initialized with the current configuration.
        Note also that this stream will be bound as a result of the call.

        Parameters:
        count - the number of generated outputs.
        supplier - the supplier instance.
        Returns:
        the new stream instance.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified count number is 0 or negative.

        @NotNull
 @StreamFlow(value=MAP)
StreamChannel<IN,OUT> appendGetMore(long count,
                                                                     @NotNull
                                                                     Consumer<? super Channel<OUT,?>> consumer)
        Concatenates a stream appending the outputs returned by the specified consumer.
        The result channel of the backing routine will be passed to the consumer, so that multiple or no results may be generated.
        The consumer will be called count number of times only when the previous routine invocations complete. The count number must be positive.

        Note that the created routine will be initialized with the current configuration.
        Note also that this stream will be bound as a result of the call.

        Parameters:
        count - the number of generated outputs.
        consumer - the consumer instance.
        Returns:
        the new stream instance.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified count number is 0 or negative.

      • backoffOn

        @NotNull
 @StreamFlow(value=CONFIG)
StreamChannel<IN,OUT> backoffOn(@Nullable
                                                                    Runner runner,
                                                                    int limit,
                                                                    @NotNull
                                                                    Backoff backoff)
        Short for invocationConfiguration().withRunner(runner).withInputLimit(maxInputs) .withInputBackoff(backoff).applied().
        This method is useful to easily apply a configuration which will slow down the thread feeding the next routine concatenated to the stream, when the number of buffered inputs exceeds the specified limit. Since waiting on the same runner thread is not allowed, it is advisable to employ a runner instance different from the feeding one, so to avoid deadlock exceptions.
        Parameters:
        runner - the configured runner.
        limit - the maximum number of buffered inputs before starting to slow down the feeding thread.
        backoff - the backoff policy to apply to the feeding thread.
        Returns:
        the new stream instance.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified limit is negative.

                                                                   BiConsumer<? super OUT,? super OUT> accumulateConsumer)

         consumer.accept(acc, input);

      • retry

        @NotNull
 @StreamFlow(value=COLLECT)
StreamChannel<IN,OUT> retry(@NotNull
                                                                 BiFunction<? super Integer,? super RoutineException,? extends Long> backoffFunction)
        Returns a new stream retrying the whole flow of data until the specified function does not return null.
        For each retry the function is called passing the retry count (starting from 1) and the error which caused the failure. If the function returns a non-null value, it will represent the number of milliseconds to wait before a further retry. While, in case the function returns null, the flow of data will be aborted with the passed error as reason.

        Note that no retry will be attempted in case of an explicit abortion, that is, if the error is an instance of AbortException.

        Parameters:
        backoffFunction - the retry function.
        Returns:
        the new stream instance.

      • straight

        @NotNull
 @StreamFlow(value=CONFIG)
StreamChannel<IN,OUT> straight()
        Short for async().streamInvocationConfiguration().withRunner(straightRunner).applied().
        This method is useful to set the stream runner so that each input is immediately passed through the whole chain as soon as it is fed to the stream.

        On the contrary of the default synchronous runner, the set one makes so that each routine in the chain is passed any input as soon as it is produced by the previous one. Such behavior decreases memory demands at the expense of a deeper stack of calls. In fact, the default synchronous runner breaks up routine calls so to perform them in a loop. The main drawback of the latter approach is that all input data are accumulated before actually being processed by the next routine invocation.

        Note that the runner will be employed with asynchronous and parallel invocation modes, while the synchronous and sequential modes will behave as before.

        Returns:
        the new stream instance.
        See Also:
        async(), parallel()
